        <p xml:id="NA54-kiḷavi">itu kāmammikka kaḻipaṭar kiḷavi.</p>
        <p xml:lang="en">This is the speech [situation] of excessive affliction when desire has increased.</p>
      </div>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="NA54">
<l>            vaḷainīr mēyntu kiḷaimutaṟ celīi</l>
<l>            vāppaṟai virumpiṉai yāyiṉun tūcciṟai</l>
<l>            yirumpulā varuntaniṉ kiḷaiyoṭu ciṟitiruntu</l>
<l>            karuṅkāl veṇkuru keṉava kēṇmati</l>
<l>            perumpulam piṉṟē ciṟupuṉ mālai </l>
<l>            yatunī yaṟiyi ṉaṉpumā ruṭaiyai</l>
<l>            notuma ṉeñcaṅ koḷḷā teṉkuṟai</l>
<l>            yiṟṟāṅ kuṇara vuraimatit taḻaiyōr</l>
<l>            koykuḻai yarumpiya kumari ñāḻa</l>
<l>            ṟeṇṭirai maṇippuṟan taivaruṅ </l>
<l>            kaṇṭal vēlinun tuṟaikiḻa vōṟkē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg xml:lang="en">
<l rend="indent">Even if you, after grazing the curved waters(?)<note place="foot">This first formulaic phrase is interpreted by T.V.G. as shells grazing the water (which might refer to a phenomenon to be observed on South-Indian beaches: shells standing upright in the strip of sand perpetually flooded by waves – in groups not unlike herds of cattle on a meadow – and diving into the sands every time the water comes back). There are certainly places where we have to come back to such an interpretation, here, however, the absolutive <term xml:lang="ta">mēyntu</term> rather invites subject identity with the main clause, which would mean the <term xml:lang="ta">kuruku</term>.</note>, moving among</l>
<l rend="indent">[your] flock, are longing for leaping flight, [you with] pure wings,</l>
<l>stay a little [longer] with your flock to eat big flesh,</l>
<l rend="indent2">black-legged white heron,</l>
<l rend="indent4">[and] listen to what [I] say:</l>
<l>very lonely is this small bleak evening.</l>
<l rend="indent3">When you know that, you really(?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">aṉpu-mār</term>: here <term xml:lang="ta">-mār</term> presumably must be one of the rarer "expletives". What nuance of emphasis does it give? Parallels?</note></l>
<l rend="indent2">do possess love. Without taking on an indifferent heart</l>
<l>speak, so that [he] realises my want as such,<note place="foot">Here it seems possible to observe a blend of the semantic meaning of <term xml:lang="ta">kuṟai</term> as a deficiency (i.e., something that is missing, namely HIS presence to HER) and the poetological usage as a request (usually made by HIM to the confidante).</note></l>
<l>to the lord of your ghat with mangrove fences,</l>
<l rend="indent2">where the sapphire backs of the clear waves rub on the maiden</l>
<l rend="indent2">Ñāḻal<note place="foot">Cf. KT 347.2, where we find a <term xml:lang="ta">kumari vākai</term>, a maiden Sirissa.</note> trees that have budded sprouts to be plucked</l>
<l rend="indent3">by those who wear foliage.</l>
    
        </lg>
